        { type: 'paragraph', text: 'MacIntyre would further argue that Beauvoir\'s emphasis on radical individual freedom as the foundation of ethics is precisely the disease masquerading as the cure. The modern self, stripped of all substantive communal identity and handed nothing but its own naked freedom, is not liberated but impoverished — incapable of genuine moral reasoning because it lacks the shared traditions and practices that give moral concepts their meaning. For MacIntyre, the virtues are not chosen in some dramatic existential act of self-creation; they are cultivated over time within specific communities whose practices embody a living tradition of inquiry into the good. Beauvoir\'s "serious man" who follows tradition uncritically is indeed morally deficient, MacIntyre might concede, but the existentialist who rejects all tradition in favor of pure freedom is equally lost — perhaps more so, because they have no resources for distinguishing genuine moral insight from arbitrary preference.' }
