    bio: 'Hannah Arendt was born in Hanover, Germany, to a secular Jewish family and grew up in Königsberg, the city of Kant. She studied philosophy under Martin Heidegger at the University of Marburg — a relationship that would prove both intellectually formative and personally tumultuous — before completing her doctorate under Karl Jaspers at Heidelberg in 1929 with a dissertation on the concept of love in Augustine. The rise of Nazism forced her into political engagement; she was briefly arrested by the Gestapo in 1933 for researching antisemitic propaganda, after which she fled Germany, living as a stateless refugee in Paris before emigrating to the United States in 1941.\n\nIn America, Arendt became one of the most important political thinkers of the twentieth century. Her 1951 masterwork "The Origins of Totalitarianism" traced the roots of Nazi and Stalinist regimes through imperialism, antisemitism, and the dissolution of the nation-state, establishing her as a major public intellectual. "The Human Condition" (1958) offered a profound analysis of the active life — labor, work, and action — arguing that political action, the capacity to begin something genuinely new in concert with others, is the highest expression of human freedom. Her 1963 report on the trial of Adolf Eichmann in Jerusalem introduced the controversial concept of "the banality of evil," suggesting that the most catastrophic moral failures often stem not from demonic wickedness but from thoughtlessness — the failure to think from the standpoint of another.\n\nArendt held positions at the University of Chicago, the New School for Social Research, and was the first woman appointed as a full professor at Princeton. She was a fiercely independent thinker who resisted categorization: she rejected the label "philosopher" in favor of "political theorist," and her work drew criticism from Zionists, Marxists, and liberals alike. Her later writings on judgment, truth in politics, and the life of the mind remain essential reading for anyone grappling with the relationship between thought and political responsibility. She died in New York City in 1975, leaving behind an unfinished work on the faculty of judgment.',
